title: For Sale:  Taurus .45 .410 Judge model 4410 3 inch Chamber 4 inch Barrel Stainless 45 Long Colt and 410 gauge Shotgun Shell Shotshell Interchangeably Near Mint in Box 2441049MAG .45/.410
postcontent:
Our # HG2441049MAGU

This listing is for One revolver. Dealers, Departments and Collectors, however, are welcome to take any number of virtually identical specimens we might have on Hand. Revolvers chambered in .45 Colt caliber have multitasked for many years. Thompson Center’s Contender barrel created quite a stir forty years ago, with heated discussion over whether it constituted a sawed off shotgun. California Attorney General Bill Lockyer classified it as such. Taurus introduced its Judge series at the 2006 SHOT Show, by our poor memory, and it has made enough of a splash that Smith & Wesson followed with the Governor four years later. What is distinctive, of course, about the Taurus Judge is that while it fires .45 Colt caliber ammunition very well, it will also chamber and fire .410 gauge shotgun shells. This one, unlike many of its siblings, will chamber and fire 3 inch .410 shells. Manufacturer is Forjas Taurus, S.A., of Porto Alegre, Brazil. Importer is Taurus International of Miami. Numbered model is 4410; factory order number is 2-441049MAG, and this is one of the harder to find variants. Construction is entirely stainless steel, with the exception of internal springs and the front sight housing. Finish is satin stainless, with hard finish stainless hammer and trigger. Barrel is one piece, 4 inch 1:12 rifling with shallow grooves. Front sight is dovetailed blue steel housing a high visibility red fiber optic tube, with frame integral fixed groove rear sight. Trigger is .395 smooth face combat type with matching width semi-target serrated short spur hammer. Ignition is floating firing pin, and the hammer operates against a transfer bar safety device, and also houses Taurus’s patented internal hammer lock. Ejector rod is checkered serration stainless, and Taurus’s detent locking system for the cylinder yoke ensures stability with dual cylinder anchoring. Grips are Taurus Factory Ribber with horizontal serrations, sure gripping and recoil absorbent. Overall length is 9 inches. Weight empty is a well balanced 37 1/2 ounces with center of gravity at the front guard junction. This judge holds 5 rounds of U.S. Made .410 gauge 2 1/2 inch or 3 inch Shotshell, or any brand of .45 Colt Caliber ammunition. Judges exhibit difficulty in extracting imported .410 spent hulls, but no problems at all with any of the big three U.S. Manufacturers – Federal, Winchester, or Remington. This specimen is what we call a factory demo, most likely a sales rep’s sample that served as a showgirl in industry trade shows like the annual SHOT Show in Las Vegas. It was manufactured in 2012 or 2013. Box is marked, Factory Reconditioned, as the photos show. That sticker simply means that Taurus will service this revolver for any mechanical issues, but will not perform a freebie refinish. It does not need a refinish anyway. Surface detractions are minimal to negligible, really no more cylinder rotation marking than brand new specimens on display in gun shops. Bore, cylinder chambers, and mechanism are all bright and clean. It comes in its original box with two keys for its hammer lock, protective wrappers, and instruction manual. Replacement pricing on this Judge is upwards of $700 in our area. We’re offering the 3 inch chambered, 4 inch barreled Judge in the photos, however, or one of its identical mates,		 for only 	$ 459.00.  Not transferable to civilian residents of California, the District of Colombia, or Massachusetts. Any ammunition showing in our photos is NOT included. Shooting watermelons is considered sacrilegious in Tennessee and Mississippi.

title: For Sale:  H&R Buffalo Classic Rifle 45-70 NIB
postcontent:
Buffalo Classic Rifle
Big medicine for those born 100 years too late. The sporting tradition, American history and good ol’ fashioned quality craftsmanship come together in this big-bore rifle built to celebrate a legacy that began in 1871. Modeled after the Frank Wesson tip-up rifles that were first made in Worcester, Massachusetts in the 1850s. Chambered for the 45-70 Gov't. cartridge, this rifle reflects true 19th century styling with antique color case hardening on the frame and a crescent butt plate. Its handsome American walnut stocks and fore-ends are accentuated by cut checkering.

Buffalo Classic Rifle
Traditional styling and aiming stability were foremost in its design. Offered in 45-70 Gov’t., its 32" midweight barrel helps this big-bore cartridge develop full velocity and accuracy potential. It also provides the necessary sighting radius for long-range matches. The Williams receiver sight is complemented by a traditional globe-style target front sight with eight aperture inserts.

This is an Enfield No4Mk1 rifle dated to ~1943. The rear sight has been replaced (reversibly and non-damagingly! thank the lord) with an SK Mounts Picatinny mount (these sell for ~$80 alone) and is topped with a Eurolux 2-8x36 scope. Eurolux is some defunct Chinese company from the 80s as far as I can tell. The scope works fine and has held zero for many hunting trips being dragged through the woods.  All other parts are original and historically accurate. 

I do not have the original rear sight unfortunately. They're available from Nurmrich or whatever other fine purveyor of gun parts suits your fancy for around $30, as these are not uncommon rifles.
